import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---
<DocsLayout title="High Availability Setup">
  <h1>High Availability Setup</h1>
  <p>
    EncodeSwarmr supports an active-passive high-availability model for production deployments that require fault
    tolerance and minimal downtime. HA is coordinated through the shared PostgreSQL database with no additional
    external consensus service required.
  </p>

  <h2>Overview: Active-Passive Model</h2>
  <p>
    In HA mode, two or more controller instances run simultaneously and share a single PostgreSQL database. At any
    given moment exactly one instance is <strong>active</strong> (processing jobs, dispatching work to agents,
    writing state) while the remaining instances are <strong>standby</strong>. Standby instances serve read-only
    API requests and health checks but do not dispatch jobs.
  </p>
  <p>
    When the active controller becomes unavailable a standby detects the stale lock and promotes itself to active
    within the configured <code>lock_timeout</code> window (default 30 seconds). No manual intervention is required.
  </p>

  <h2>Leader Election</h2>
  <p>
    Leader election is implemented using a <strong>PostgreSQL advisory lock</strong>. The mechanism works as follows:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>On startup each controller instance attempts to acquire a well-known advisory lock ID via <code>pg_try_advisory_lock()</code></li>
    <li>The first instance to succeed becomes the <strong>active leader</strong> and begins processing jobs</li>
    <li>The active leader refreshes the lock on a configurable interval (<code>lock_refresh_interval</code>, default 5 s) by executing a heartbeat query</li>
    <li>Standby instances poll PostgreSQL for the lock owner. If the lock has not been refreshed within <code>lock_timeout</code> (default 30 s) the standby calls <code>pg_try_advisory_lock()</code> and, if successful, transitions to active</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Because the advisory lock is tied to the database connection, a crashed or network-partitioned controller
    automatically releases the lock when its connection drops, enabling fast failover without a split-brain scenario.
  </p>
  <pre><code># controller.yml — HA configuration block
ha:
  enabled: true
  lock_refresh_interval: 5s   # How often the active leader refreshes its lock
  lock_timeout: 30s           # How long before a stale lock is considered expired</code></pre>

  <h2>Node Identity</h2>
  <p>
    Each controller instance is assigned a stable node identity used in HA status reporting, logs, and the
    <code>/api/v1/ha/status</code> endpoint. The identity defaults to the system hostname but can be overridden:
  </p>
  <pre><code>ha:
  enabled: true
  node_id: "controller-01"    # Optional; defaults to os.Hostname()</code></pre>

  <h2>Health and Status Endpoints</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Endpoint</th><th>Method</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>/health</code></td>
        <td>GET</td>
        <td>Returns HTTP 200 with role (<code>active</code> or <code>standby</code>). Use this for load balancer health checks.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>/api/v1/ha/status</code></td>
        <td>GET</td>
        <td>Returns detailed HA status: node ID, role, lock holder, last heartbeat timestamp, and cluster membership list.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <pre><code># GET /health — active instance
&#123;"status": "ok", "role": "active", "version": "1.0.0"&#125;

# GET /health — standby instance
&#123;"status": "ok", "role": "standby", "version": "1.0.0"&#125;

# GET /api/v1/ha/status
&#123;
  "node_id": "controller-01",
  "role": "active",
  "lock_holder": "controller-01",
  "last_heartbeat": "2026-03-24T10:00:05Z",
  "cluster": [
    &#123;"node_id": "controller-01", "role": "active",  "healthy": true&#125;,
    &#123;"node_id": "controller-02", "role": "standby", "healthy": true&#125;
  ]
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2>Agent Reconnection</h2>
  <p>
    Agents are designed to survive controller failover transparently:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>The agent's gRPC connection to the active controller drops when the active instance fails</li>
    <li>The agent detects the disconnection immediately via the gRPC keepalive mechanism</li>
    <li>The agent enters a reconnect loop with exponential backoff (initial 1 s, max 30 s) connecting to the load balancer address — not a specific controller IP</li>
    <li>Once the standby promotes to active (within <code>lock_timeout</code>) and the load balancer health check passes, the agent reconnects and resumes work. Any in-progress chunk completes locally and its result is buffered in the SQLite journal until the connection is re-established</li>
  </ol>
  <p>No manual intervention is required on the agent side during a failover event.</p>

  <h2>Docker Compose Example</h2>
  <p>Full two-controller HA stack with nginx as the load balancer:</p>
  <pre><code># docker-compose.ha.yml
version: "3.9"

services:
  postgres:
    image: postgres:16-alpine
    restart: unless-stopped
    environment:
      POSTGRES_DB: encodeswarmr
      POSTGRES_USER: encodeswarmr
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: changeme
    volumes:
      - postgres_data:/var/lib/postgresql/data
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD-SHELL", "pg_isready -U encodeswarmr"]
      interval: 5s
      timeout: 3s
      retries: 10

  controller-1:
    image: ghcr.io/badskater/encodeswarmr-controller:latest
    restart: unless-stopped
    depends_on:
      postgres:
        condition: service_healthy
    environment:
      DE_DB_HOST: postgres
      DE_DB_PORT: "5432"
      DE_DB_NAME: encodeswarmr
      DE_DB_USER: encodeswarmr
      DE_DB_PASSWORD: changeme
      DE_HTTP_ADDR: "0.0.0.0:8080"
      DE_GRPC_ADDR: "0.0.0.0:9443"
      DE_TLS_CA_CERT: /etc/encodeswarmr/certs/ca.crt
      DE_TLS_SERVER_CERT: /etc/encodeswarmr/certs/server.crt
      DE_TLS_SERVER_KEY: /etc/encodeswarmr/certs/server.key
      DE_SECRET_KEY: replace-with-32-byte-random-string
      DE_HA_ENABLED: "true"
      DE_HA_NODE_ID: "controller-1"
      DE_HA_LOCK_REFRESH_INTERVAL: "5s"
      DE_HA_LOCK_TIMEOUT: "30s"
    volumes:
      - ./certs:/etc/encodeswarmr/certs:ro
      - media:/mnt/media

  controller-2:
    image: ghcr.io/badskater/encodeswarmr-controller:latest
    restart: unless-stopped
    depends_on:
      postgres:
        condition: service_healthy
    environment:
      DE_DB_HOST: postgres
      DE_DB_PORT: "5432"
      DE_DB_NAME: encodeswarmr
      DE_DB_USER: encodeswarmr
      DE_DB_PASSWORD: changeme
      DE_HTTP_ADDR: "0.0.0.0:8080"
      DE_GRPC_ADDR: "0.0.0.0:9443"
      DE_TLS_CA_CERT: /etc/encodeswarmr/certs/ca.crt
      DE_TLS_SERVER_CERT: /etc/encodeswarmr/certs/server.crt
      DE_TLS_SERVER_KEY: /etc/encodeswarmr/certs/server.key
      DE_SECRET_KEY: replace-with-32-byte-random-string
      DE_HA_ENABLED: "true"
      DE_HA_NODE_ID: "controller-2"
      DE_HA_LOCK_REFRESH_INTERVAL: "5s"
      DE_HA_LOCK_TIMEOUT: "30s"
    volumes:
      - ./certs:/etc/encodeswarmr/certs:ro
      - media:/mnt/media

  nginx:
    image: nginx:alpine
    restart: unless-stopped
    ports:
      - "8080:8080"
      - "9443:9443"
    volumes:
      - ./nginx.conf:/etc/nginx/nginx.conf:ro
    depends_on:
      - controller-1
      - controller-2

volumes:
  postgres_data:
  media:</code></pre>

  <h3>Minimal <code>nginx.conf</code></h3>
  <pre><code>events &#123;&#125;

http &#123;
  upstream controllers_http &#123;
    server controller-1:8080;
    server controller-2:8080;
  &#125;

  server &#123;
    listen 8080;
    location / &#123;
      proxy_pass http://controllers_http;
      proxy_set_header Host $host;
      proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;

stream &#123;
  upstream controllers_grpc &#123;
    server controller-1:9443;
    server controller-2:9443;
  &#125;

  server &#123;
    listen 9443;
    proxy_pass controllers_grpc;
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2>PostgreSQL HA with Patroni</h2>
  <p>
    For database-level high availability, EncodeSwarmr recommends <strong>Patroni</strong> with
    <strong>pgBouncer</strong> for connection pooling:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Patroni</strong> — Manages PostgreSQL streaming replication and automatic primary failover using etcd, Consul, or ZooKeeper as the distributed configuration store</li>
    <li><strong>pgBouncer</strong> — Sits in front of Patroni and transparently re-routes connections to the current primary after a failover; the controller configuration always points at the pgBouncer address</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Considerations when using Patroni:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Advisory locks are connection-scoped — ensure pgBouncer is configured in <strong>session</strong> pooling mode (not transaction mode) so the advisory lock persists for the lifetime of the controller connection</li>
    <li>Use <code>server_idle_timeout = 0</code> in pgBouncer to prevent idle connections from being dropped and releasing the advisory lock prematurely</li>
    <li>During a Patroni failover (PostgreSQL primary switch) the controller advisory lock will be released. Expect a brief HA re-election cycle (≤ <code>lock_timeout</code>) as both controllers reconnect and one acquires the new lock</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Failure Scenarios</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Detection</th><th>Recovery Time</th><th>Agent Impact</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Active controller process crash</td>
        <td>PostgreSQL connection drop releases advisory lock immediately</td>
        <td>&lt; 5 s (standby acquires lock on next poll)</td>
        <td>Brief reconnect; in-progress chunks continue locally</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Active controller host failure (power / kernel panic)</td>
        <td>PostgreSQL TCP keepalive detects dead connection within ~30 s</td>
        <td>30–60 s (TCP timeout + lock acquisition)</td>
        <td>Agents buffer results in SQLite journal; no chunk loss</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Network partition (active controller loses DB connectivity)</td>
        <td>Active controller cannot refresh lock; lock expires after <code>lock_timeout</code></td>
        <td>≤ <code>lock_timeout</code> (default 30 s)</td>
        <td>Agents lose gRPC stream; reconnect after failover</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>PostgreSQL primary failover (Patroni)</td>
        <td>All controllers lose DB connection; reconnect to new primary via pgBouncer</td>
        <td>Patroni failover (10–30 s) + lock re-election (≤ 30 s)</td>
        <td>Same as network partition above</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Load balancer failure</td>
        <td>Agents cannot connect to load balancer address</td>
        <td>Depends on LB HA (cloud LBs are inherently redundant)</td>
        <td>Agents buffer results until LB recovers</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</DocsLayout>
